{"id":"1907.10598","submitter":"Peter Schuck","authors":"Peter W. Schuck, Spiro K. Antiochos","title":"Determining the Transport of Magnetic Helicity and Free Energy in the\n  Sun's Atmosphere","comments":"35 pages, 3 figures, Accepted for Publication in the Astrophysical\n  Journal","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/ab298a","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The most important factors determining solar coronal activity are believed to\nbe the availability of magnetic free energy and the constraint of magnetic\nhelicity conservation. Direct measurements of the helicity and magnetic free\nenergy in the coronal volume are difficult, but their values may be estimated\nfrom measurements of the helicity and free energy transport rates through the\nphotosphere. We examine these transport rates for a topologically open system\nsuch as the corona, in which the magnetic fields have a nonzero normal\ncomponent at the boundaries, and derive a new formula for the helicity\ntransport rate at the boundaries. In addition, we derive new expressions for\nhelicity transport due to flux emergence/submergence versus photospheric\nhorizontal motions. The key feature of our formulas is that they are manifestly\ngauge invariant. Our results are somewhat counterintuitive in that only the\nlamellar electric field produced by the surface potential transports helicity\nacross boundaries, and the solenoidal electric field produced by a surface\nstream function does not contribute to the helicity transport. We discuss the\nphysical interpretation of this result. Furthermore, we derive an expression\nfor the free energy transport rate and show that a necessary condition for free\nenergy transport across a boundary is the presence of a closed magnetic field\nat the surface, indicating that there are current systems within the volume. We\ndiscuss the implications of these results for using photospheric